@prabhjyotsingh Cool improvement!

I tried. And found that i can access notebook without login after enables authentication by editing shiro.ini.

```
#/** = anon
/** = authc
```

@elbamos :  One thought:  The `-Ppyspark` build profile will download the spark distribution in order to pass tests and include pyspark in build the distribution with all required spark dependencies.
Is there an equivalent for this PR to work with CI?
It might also lead to some benefits for the future `-Pbuild-distr` work.

@jeffsteinmetz I'm not sure I understand what you're proposing?

At this moment this PR isn't failing CI.  It builds and tests fine.  

When CI later tries to use a recently-added test class that has nothing to do with this PR, the class tries to talk to Spark, but Spark isn't running.

@elbamos removing test that do not pass under b848d98 is not an acceptable way to make CI green. 
It is not going to be possible to merge it without `ZeppelinSparkClusterTest.java` I'm affraid. 

Please put it back and let's fix the reason it is failing on this branch.

@bzz It does make sense. Tom's proposal, which everyone liked, was to merge this into a feature version branch, and we can all use that to track down the CI issue.  

One of you needs to that -- I can't.

Also -- will you be looking at the causes of these failures?  It appears to me that this is exactly the same issue as its been all along, which is that Spark does not reliably launch in CI.

@bzz I don't know what the implications are of those options.  

Honestly, I feel like if we spend time on that, its going to be a distraction, because I have a suspicion that if there is a non-obvious bug here, and you wrote the testing infrastructure, that the bug is going to be found 15 minutes after someone starts looking.  

Can you take a look at what's going on in the push when I removed the test class?  What concerns me here is not that the tests that had failed, started to pass --- its that the tests that had passed before, started to _fail_ after the test was deleted.

@bzz I will look into junit ignore.  Regarding the licenses, that issue is where it has been:  For files that are forked from other things, but also contain changes, I need to know where you would like the licenses to go. 

What is necessary is simply a _decision_.    We can't just put the apache header in those files, because some of the content is covered by another license.  Currently those files are identified in the "other licenses" file -- but, the portion of the files that has _changed_, is covered by the Apache license. 

So, again, what's necessary here is simply the _decision_, and because it is a licensing issue, it cannot be made by anyone but a member of the PPMC.

@elbamos got it, but could you please post your answers in the comments that I have made and linked from the list, so we have full conversation history online? 

Please keep in mind that I'm asking not because I want so, but because when somebody later on will be curious about the decision we made here, he could just follow the links and read your answers, without the need to follow all hundreds of comments in this thread. 

So it will just save the time for future reviewers, that's it. Hope this make sense.
